# Buzzer and Digital Inputs

## 1. Overview
In this lesson, you will learn how to connect and use a buzzer along with a
push button as a digital input.

## 2. Components required

* Development board
* Breadboard 830p
* 1 x push button
* 1 x passive buzzer
* Diode
* Transistor
* 1 x 1000 Ω resistor
* 10 x male-to-male jumper wires
* Micro USB – Type A USB cable

## 3. Connections
  Below you can find the schematic:

This scheme looks a little complicated, so let's simplify it by using some new electrical symbols. Sometimes, on really busy schematics, you can assign special symbols to node voltages. You can connect devices to these one-terminal symbols,
and it'll be tied directly to 5V, 3.3V, VCC, or GND (ground).

For GND (ground) we will use the first symbol and for +3.3V we will use the second symbol :
Using the above defined symbols, our scheme is equivalent with:

We will be using these symbols when our schemes will be too complicated to follow, so keep them in mind. Also, below is a visual representation of the project, check it too for a better understanding.

In the next diagram we have as main elements the button, the transistor and the buzzer.

To connect the button we will make the connection of the pins on the diagonal to avoid the short circuit. 

The transistor will have the collector pin connected to ground, the base pin connected by a resistor to one of the pins on the board and the emitting pin will be connected to our buzzer by a diode to avoid polarity reversal. 

The other pin of the buzzer is connected to the voltage.

## 4. Code

### Import libraries
First, we import libraries to later use the functions and variables predefined in them.

#use these libraries to declare used pins and PWM
from machine import Pin, PWM
#for delay
from time import sleep

### Declaration variables
The code starts with the declaration of the pins used by the button and the buzzer. 

We fisrt declare as an input pin ('Pin.IN') and pull up pin ('Pin.PULL_UP') the button and as output pin ('Pin.OUT') the buzzer.
With the initiation of the pin used by the buzzer, we declare it as PWM.

The button is connected to D1 (GPIO**5**) and the buzzer is connected to D6 (GPIO**12**).

#define the pine used by the button
#also initialise the button as INPUT, PULL_UP 
button = Pin(5, Pin.IN, Pin.PULL_UP) #D1
#define the pin as OUTPUT and the PWM of the buzzer 
buzzer = PWM(Pin(12, Pin.OUT) , freq = 500)

### Infinite loop

We will create an infinite loop ('while True') for the board to execute the instructions continuously.

In the this while loop we have to read the state of the button using button.value(), and if the button is pressed (button.value() == 0), the buzzer will turn on at a frequency of 1000 Hz (you can modify this frequency). 

After the if statement we need to put an elif to stop the buzzer, if the button is pushed down, we need something to keep the infinite loop in running.

If we leave the while with no instructions to do, the board will crash, because it will stay too long in a while loop and other processes will not be able to run.

#for board execute the instructions continuously we make an infinite loop
while True:
    # read the current state of the button
    #if the button is pressed, turn on the buzzer
    if button.value() == 0:
        #we use a frequency of 1kHz(1000Hz)
        #you can change this frequency so the sound can be
        #more pleasant
        buzzer.duty(1000)
    #if the button is pushed down, we need something
    #to keep the infinite loop function from running
    elif button.value():
        #if we leave the while with no instructions to do
        #the board will crash, because it will stay too long
        #in a while loop and other processes will not be able to run
        buzzer.deinit()

Next step is to gently connect the development board to the computer via the
included micro USB cable. There is only one way to plug it in, do not use force to
insert the cable.

To compile the code you should follow the instructions for the board *Adafruit CLUE* from this
 [Demo](https://youtu.be/F_4GXU8kKfk?t=585) .

**Congratulations**, you have completed the tutorial!
